=========================================================
MEMORY LAYOUT OF A C++ PROGRAM (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

A typical C++ program memory is divided into:

---------------------------------------------------------
| Command Line Arguments / Environment Variables        |
---------------------------------------------------------
|                        Stack                          |
---------------------------------------------------------
|                         ↓                             |
|                    Free Memory                        |
|                         ↑                             |
---------------------------------------------------------
|                         Heap                          |
---------------------------------------------------------
|                  BSS Segment (.bss)                  |
---------------------------------------------------------
|               Initialized Data (.data)               |
---------------------------------------------------------
|              Read-Only Data (.rodata)                |
---------------------------------------------------------
|               Text/Code Segment (.text)              |
---------------------------------------------------------

=========================================================
1. TEXT / CODE SEGMENT (.text)
=========================================================

Stores:
• Compiled machine instructions
• Function code
• Read-only executable code

Characteristics:
• Read-only
• Shared among processes
• Exists throughout program execution

Example:

void fun()
{
    cout << "Hello";
}

Machine code of fun() is stored in .text.

=========================================================
2. READ-ONLY DATA SEGMENT (.rodata)
=========================================================

Stores:
• String literals
• const global variables (typically)

Example:

char* str = "Hello";

"Hello" is stored in:

.rodata

Attempting modification:

str[0] = 'A';

Undefined Behavior.

=========================================================
3. INITIALIZED DATA SEGMENT (.data)
=========================================================

Stores:
• Global variables
• Static variables
• Explicitly initialized

Example:

int x = 100;

static int y = 200;

Stored in:

.data

Characteristics:
• Read/Write
• Lifetime = Entire program execution

=========================================================
4. BSS SEGMENT (.bss)
=========================================================

(BSS = Block Started by Symbol)

Stores:
• Uninitialized global variables
• Uninitialized static variables
• Variables initialized to zero

Example:

int x;

static int y;

int z = 0;

Stored in:

.bss

Characteristics:
• Automatically initialized to 0.
• Lifetime = Entire program execution.

=========================================================
5. HEAP SEGMENT
=========================================================

Stores:
• Dynamically allocated memory

Allocated using:

new
delete

Example:

int* ptr = new int(10);

Memory:

ptr (Stack)
 ↓
[10] (Heap)

Characteristics:
• Runtime allocation
• Programmer managed
• Large memory area
• Can cause memory leaks

=========================================================
6. STACK SEGMENT
=========================================================

Stores:
• Local variables
• Function parameters
• Return addresses
• Function call information

Example:

void fun()
{
    int x = 10;
}

x is stored on:

Stack

Characteristics:
• Automatic allocation/deallocation
• Fast
• Limited size
• Scope based

=========================================================
EXAMPLE PROGRAM
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int g = 100;          // .data
int g2;               // .bss
const int c = 50;     // .rodata (typically)

void fun()
{
    int x = 10;       // Stack

    int* ptr =
        new int(20);  // Heap
}

int main()
{
    fun();
}

=========================================================
MEMORY MAPPING
=========================================================

int g = 100;          → .data
int g2;               → .bss
const int c = 50;     → .rodata
fun() code            → .text
int x                 → Stack
new int(20)           → Heap

