=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. Where are local variables stored?

Answer:
Stack.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Where is dynamically allocated memory stored?

Answer:
Heap.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Where are global initialized variables stored?

Answer:
.data segment.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Where are uninitialized global/static variables stored?

Answer:
.bss segment.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Where are string literals stored?

Answer:
.rodata (Read-only data segment).

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Where is function code stored?

Answer:
.text segment.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Why is Stack faster than Heap?

Answer:
Stack allocation is simple push/pop operation.
Heap requires complex allocation algorithms.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Which memory region can cause memory leaks?

Answer:
Heap.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. Lifetime of global variables?

Answer:
Entire program execution.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. Lifetime of local variables?

Answer:
Till the function scope ends.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

A C++ program's memory is divided into Text (.text), Read-Only Data
(.rodata), Initialized Data (.data), BSS (.bss), Heap, and Stack.
Function code resides in .text, string literals in .rodata, initialized
globals/statics in .data, uninitialized globals/statics in .bss,
dynamic memory in Heap, and local variables and function call frames in
Stack.

